Incorrect Caching Policy Can Break Your App

SPAs

Single-page applications are a popular way of creating websites nowadays. The main difference from multi-page applications is that single-page apps download each page once. As soon as a user interacts with the app, required components are modified without reloading the whole application again. This makes a single-page app much faster and offers a much better user experience. Users don’t wait for the whole page to re-render, they only have to wait for the loading indicator and the content is loaded faster.

But this approach brings a variety of new difficulties and possible bugs.

The Challenge

It takes much more time and effort to create a single page application as opposed to a multi-page one. Developers need to deal with way more states and problems, and since the application runs for a longer time more unwanted bugs may appear. And I will tell you a story of one of our interesting bugs which troubled us for quite a long time.

From time to time, some of our users saw a white screen instead of our application when a new version was released. It only happened in the production version of the application, we didn’t come across it either on the dev or on the staging environments. At first it was just a few users and hitting the refresh button would solve the issue. We didn’t pay much attention to it — we thought that the problem was either due to the user’s browser or maybe regarding their internet connection.

But with every new release, more and more users experienced this issue and it became clear that it was a real problem. Of course, none of the developers had encountered this problem before, so we couldn’t get more information. Fortunately, one of the users sent us a screenshot with an open console which helped us a lot:

Looking at the console log, we found that the browser has a problem parsing some of the files because their MIME type did not match the expected one. However, we were unable to load given files, because the whole path was not visible in the screenshot.

Troubleshooting — First Steps

It was challenging to troubleshoot. Not all users experienced the issue and refreshing the page usually helped. Furthermore the problematic part was that it only happened in a production environment. Local and testing environments worked flawlessly.

So we started by having several browsers open each time we deployed, waiting to see if we were lucky enough to encounter the issue. Several deployments later, one of us finally saw the white screen! Hooray!

When we tried to load the problematic file, we found out that the MIME type (‘text/html’) being sent was fine. The file did not exist and Nginx returned a 404 html file. But why? When we checked the built image all the other files were present and uncorrupted.

We immediately realized that this was probably a caching issue. Since the beginning, we thought about unwanted file caching, so when we started dividing the application bundle into chunks and we added a hash to each chunk that changed with each build. So there wouldn’t be a problem with individual chunks.

output: {
 publicPath: ‘/’,
 chunkFilename: ‘[name].[contenthash].js’,
},

When we tried to find a file with the given hash in the name in the older images, we found that it was almost a month old. How is this possible?

Chances were the browser probably cached the main.js file. It didn’t load new main.js and so the chunk names were not the correct ones. And therefore it got 404s.

Fixed!

Once we knew what caused the problem, fixing it was easy. We just added a hash to the name of the main js file during each build, just like we did with the individual chunks. The browser would always load the main file and thanks to that it would know the paths to the chunks. This should have fixed our issue. Simply adjust the webpack configuration:

output: {
 publicPath: ‘/’,
 chunkFilename: ‘[name].[contenthash].js’,
 filename: ‘[name].[contenthash].js’,
},

We deployed new versions a few times and no one saw the white screen. We patted our shoulders and proudly added a white screen bug fix to the change log…

Fixed?

However, we were really surprised when another user reported white screen issue after a while. How is it possible? Okay, back to square one. The problem is definitely that the browser is caching something somewhere, but why?

  • We set pragma and cache control headers and believed that it should prevent the browser from caching the html file.
  • We added a hash to the main.js filename, so the browser should not cache it.
  • Same for the chunks, we had hash in their filenames, so that should prevent the browser from caching them as well.

Finally!

In the end, we had no choice but to start searching on the internet. The last two points had been thought out correctly, but we were surprised by the first point. According to https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Pragma, Pragma no longer prevents the browser from caching content and is used more for backward compatibility. So if we wanted to prevent browser from caching html file, it was necessary to use the cache-control header:

location = /index.html {
  add_header Cache-Control “no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate”;
}

When we found this the fix was really easy. We just added the necessary header to the Nginx configuration and it looks like everything is already working. We are hoping this solves the problem and you can learn from our mistakes. It took several days of trial and error to fix such a simple bug.

Note

We are not alone here. This is a screenshot from internet banking of one of the biggest Czech banks:

They faced the same issue and apparently it wasn’t easy and straightforward to fix it for them either.
